Now  this  mag  is REALLY interesting,
and  I suspect I will write a somewhat
lenghty   review,  so  bear  with  me.
First  off,  the  reason  why »CL6:Devotion»CL1:
isn't dead, is a tale in itself.  When
»CL2:Magic  »CL1:  released   his   »CL0:dvn2dead.lha»CL1:
archive, »CL2: Darkus»CL1: was looking for a way
to get rid of him, and still bring out
»CL6:Devotion   2»CL1:.    He   found   »CL2:Wade»CL1:  as
co-editor,  and  some others, and work
started  on issue 2.  Things didn't go
as smoothly as that however, as »CL2:Darkus»CL1:
apparently  abandoned »CL2: Wade»CL1:  at a time
when »CL6:Devotion»CL1: was finally ready to get
released.   No  emails  for weeks, and
the  mag  was practically ready.  Then
»CL2:Darkus»CL1:  answered,  saying he had had a
HD  crash, and that »CL6:Devotion»CL1: went with
it,  but  that  he  would  get back to
»CL0:recovering »CL1: the  data eventually.  No,
that  didn't  sound  very  »CL0:devoted»CL1:, so
»CL2:Wade»CL1:  decided to take matters into his
own  hands, ousting »CL2:Darkus»CL1: and most of
the   other  editors,  getting  a  bit
support  from  oldtime editor »CL2:Fishwave»CL1:
and  release »CL6:Devotion #2»CL1: with articles
mainly  from  him  and  »CL2:Sane»CL1:,  another
editor  who  had  quit  the scene some
years   ago,   when   »CL6:Seenpoint»CL1:  died.
»CL2:Ghandy  »CL1:has also written some articles
for this issue, so »CL6:DVN 2»CL1: seems to have
an    old    and   quite   experienced
»CL0:editorteam»CL1:.    This   makes   it  very
interesting, even before one reads the
articles  and  determines  the overall
style  of  the  diskmag.   But, I will
wait  with  the  articles, and look at
the other aspects first.

»CL0:Code»CL1:  wise, I will just copy and paste
most  of what I wrote for »CL6:Devotion #1»CL1:.
Not  that  I will write about the code
each  time,  when  it  does not change
significantly, but since this is a new
mag,  I  thought  that  summing up the
code once more was in its place.

Code  wise, the mag runs very well for
a »CL0: modern »CL1: mag, it is coded using »CL0:RTG»CL1:,
which  means  it  runs both on »CL0:AGA»CL1: and
»CL0:graphicscards»CL1:,  which again means that
e.g.   A2000  owners can view the mag.
I  tested  it  with both AGA and on my
EGS  gfxcard with CGX), and there were
no  problems  at all, it worked like a
»CL0:charm»CL1:.   The  mag  is multitasking and
quite   systemfriendly,   I  have  not
succeeded  in »CL0:crashing»CL1: it yet.  As for
the in-mag features, it has everything
you'd  come to expect, that is, fading
text,  multicolour fonts with gfxcard,
and  generally the mag looks and feels
like  »CL6:ROM »CL1: and derivatives, that is, a
»CL0:slider»CL1: in the bottom panel showing you
how long the article is, and moving as
you  change  page,  there are animated
»CL0:buttons»CL1:  and »CL0:musicindex»CL1:, but you can't
switch pages by moving the mouse close
to  the  end  of the screen, a feature
which  mags  in  the »CL6: ROM»CL1: design often
have (but I don't mind the lack of it,
it   gets  »CL0: annoying »CL1:  when  the  page
suddenly    switches    because    you
unintentionally   moved   your  mouse,
etc.).   Overall,  the code works well
and  feels»CL0: slick»CL1:, but there's not many
»CL0:visible»CL1:  features  in  the code, apart
from the normal ones in mags.  »CL2:Makke's»CL1:
article  in the mag about diskmags all
looking »CL0: alike»CL1:  springs  to mind (yep,
the »CL6: EC»CL1:  is  no exception, but I'm not
reviewing  our  own  mag  here, hehe).
»CL2:Mr.   Tickle»CL1: is responsible for coding
the »CL6:Devotion»CL1: engine.

Graphically,  the mag retains the nice
panels  from  »CL2:Adam/DCS»CL1:, which is fine,
since they are really good and fit the
mag   well.    »CL2:Zaac»CL1:   made  the  title
